harges are filed against the\nformer cashier of the Allegheny- nation tl j\nb\" I \\u25a0 Page 63 j\nBlotlnj? and bloodshed attend streetcar' strike\nIn Cleveland, Ohio, and arbitration Is pro\nposed. Pose 47\nQuit while you ere champion\" Is John t,. I\nSullivan's advice to president. Page 25\nKalm Introduces resolution providing for Issn- i\nsnee to San Franc'.sco of patent to YosemUe\nlands required ia the Hetch He'tchy wai\u00bbr\nproject. Pase 25\nUarry K. Thaw, in terror on witness stann.\nanswers questions incoherently. Page 25\nSenate adopts resolution to pave the way for j\nIntelligent revision of the tariff. Page 30\nPhysicians demonstrate on a dog the practi\ncability of using electricity instead of in\nesthetics. Page 30\nSeals maintain their lead-by taking an exciting\n3to 2 game from Oaks. Page 51\nThree San Francisco boys have taken\nprominent parts la athletics at Annapolis naval I\nacademy. \\u25a0 Page' 52 j\nT. H. Williams buys best of yearlings at\nBurns 4 Waterhouse sale. Page 50\nBerkeley high school wins bay counties flei<!\nday. with Oakland second. Page 51\nPalo Alto and Napa high schools defeat Cogs\nwell and Berkeley In championship baseball\ngames.' Pnge 51\nIn dual track meet Tale defeats ilarva.d\nfor the fifth successive time. Score, -CO 1-3\nto 43 4-5. Page 51\nField Mouse. 100 to 1 6bot, wins Fashion stake\n.at Belmont park.' Page\"4o\nF. J. Kilpatrlek wins j the principal race lat\nthe park a matenr driving clnb meet -.with pis\nbluet mare Princess .W. \\u25a0: Paare 50\nState league scores\u2014 Sacramento 3. Stockton I;\nFresno 4. San Francisco 0; Santa Cruz 3, Oak\nland 2: San Jose 5.' Alameda 3. Pajce 51\nBrawny men of the navy complete string of\nathletic victories over the army, by wlnnlqg\nthe tug of war and the basket ball ehtfnplou-\nRhlps. \\u25a0 Page 40\nJohnston and Srrachan play three dence, sets In\njunior tennis tournament. \"\\u25a0'\u00ab' Page 52\nRighteasy Js only favorite to score at Emery\nville track; Cloyne wina the Mare' Island\nhandicap. Page 49\nMARINE\nMuriposa arrives with sister of Prince Salmon\nof Tahiti among passenger*. Page 53\nMINING\nNevada mining stocks show generally brighter\ntone and brokers anticipate week of good mn\u00ab\nket for \\u25a0 securities.' .*_' Page 55\nLABOR\nThe American federation -of labor /urges\nactive politic* and th\u00ab pledging of all -iesn\ndldatea. Page 31\nSAN; -FRANCISCO, SUNDAY, MAY 17, 1908.\u2014 FIFTY-SIX PAGES.\nMarsden Manson, city, engineer\nwho returned yesterday with\ngrants of Lake Eleanor and\nHetch Hetchy valleys.\nKahn Moves in Hetch\nHetchy Project\nIntroduces Resolution Providing\nfor Issuance of Patent to City\nof Necessary Lands\nSPECIAL- DISPATCH .TO THE CALL\nWASHINGTON. May 16!\u2014 Representa\ntive r Kah,n today introduced a- joint\nlesolutlon directing the secretary of\nthe interior :to issue, a patent 'to y the\ncity arid county of San Francisco i of, ail\nlands necessary: to the carrying out\" of\nthe Hetch Hetchy reservoir- project up\non\" release 1 to the government -by the\ncity of an^'equal'arealbf land, which it\nnow. controls -in- the Yosemite national\npark..-->' .'\\u25a0\";'\".'\\u25a0.\\u25a0'.'.; V \\u25a0-.*''\\u25a0'\u2022:\\u25a0; '\\u25a0\\u25a0\"\\u25a0''.\\u25a0\nThe resolution is notexpected to pass\nat this session- or.'until* San Franclsca\nhas voted to jj.ulld^th.^.reservoir. \"\"A\nhearing on the resolution will be held\nby the public, land -committee Monday.\nSays Nat Goodwin Has\nNo Strings on Her\nPretty* Edna Goodrich Comes to\nM arry M cAI 11 lan and De\nfies the Comedian\nSPFCIAL DISPATCH TO THE CALL\nNEW- YORK. May 16.\u2014 Edna Good\nrich, \\u25a0 formerly Nat 'Goodwin's leading\nwoman, arrived today from Europe on\nthe steamship Kalserln Augusta Vic\ntoria -and wept directly to. the Hotel\nPlaza.' Tpnlght she chatted about her\nwedding June .lo to Harry McMillan,; a\nwealthy mining man of -Goldfleld. She\nwill become a bride. at .the home of Mc-\nMillan's Invalid mother. In -Berkeley. As\n\"Fraulein Adams\" Miss Goodrich at\ntempted tt> evade the reporters, who\nshe knew, would be,, waiting\" for her\nat the*, pier.\n\"Mr. Goodwin has no strings on me,\"\nshe said; r \"my. contract! has 'expired.\"\nMcMillan .was not', at/ the Hpboken\npier to meet. the^beauty, but I Miss Good\nrich \\u25a0 was v not' disappointed. She said\nthat she was not v expectihg him, as\nthere were mining 'troubles in Nevada,\nwhich necessitated -his^presence there.\nWith Miss Goodrich was her. mother.\n\"I wish' you would Vdeny^ the silly,\nstories about .the wonderful trousseau\nthat I'm supposed to have purchased tin\nParis. I/did not have time to ]_ gather\nany wonderful outfit. As 'for! fur coats\nreaching :to 'my heels arid ;costing\n$10,000\u2014 piffle piffle.\" V\nThere was a rumor., about: the Ho\nboken. pier that Miss 'Goodrich had. re\nceived bad news.' She 'nearly fainted\nwhile coming down the gangplank.-She\nI denied the bad rrfews and her\nj weakness on a' severe attack of sea\nsickness. i.\nFOOLISH GIRL, SAYS NAT\nGoodwin Says Edna Was Afraid\nto Meet Him- '\\u25a0\\u25a0'+'\\u25a0-, \\u25a0\u2022\nSPECIAL\" DISI'ATCH TO THE CALL \\u25a0\nLONDON. 'May>li^Nat Goodwin' Is\nall' broken, up' oyer.^the :loss of: Edna\nGoodrich, his leading /woman.\" /After\ninstituting a search party of detectives\nhe discoveredahatthVeluslve Edna had\nescaped to' America.'- He. said 1 today:\n\\u25a0;'Toor.^foollsh:liUle 'girl; Vi, suppose\nshe was afraid to meet me. Her guilty\nconscience ha^th' made^a coward of her.'\nPoor, foolish child; she' Is not, a: great\nactress.; but r 4aave\\made 'something; of\nher. iVintfoduced\"Harry McMillan- to\nher myself .at mjrplace in\": Los? Angeles;\nShe conceived' the idea\"\u00abth'at Harry was\nrich.; Now; he j* a'jjnice \\u0084 fellow, 'but\nfinancially he.'is-a four, nusher.'v\n\nDELEGATES U^iySTKo^VED'\n\\u25a0 OLE AN. :N. ;V4 VMay ,i6.-.At:.the!re-\nRublican,;(soav.enUon of; the .Tnirty-sev-'\nenth: congressional; district! today iE.; ,B.:\n.Vreeland ;was renorain\nated r-for representatives.: j-.TheJ'dele\n.gates ;to the natibnirconvention are\nunlnstructed.\nMANSON BRINGS\nDOCUMENTS IN\nCITY'S VICTORY\nSan Francisco to Have Finest\nWater Supply in the World,\nEngineer Asserts\nProperty Worth 1 5,000,000 Is\nOffered by Government\nfor $200,000\nStupendous Task Brought to a\nSuccessful End by Energy\nof Official\nOn April 7 City Engineer Marsdcn\nManson left for Washington. Yester\nday he came back, carrying in his bat\ntered leather grip the documents, all\nduly signed, sealed and delivered,\nwhereby the United States' govern\nment grants to the city of San Fran\ncisco* the Lake Eleanor and Hetch\nHctchy water rights.\nIt was a great achievement for his\ncity and for himself, this .victory that\nMarsdcn Manson won at Washington.\nThe task was big enough for a man of\n\u2022his energy, tact, patience and exact in\nformation. He performed it in such a\nmanner as to earn for him the lasting\ngratitude of- the. people- whose inter\nests he served so well. Before long\nSan Francisco will have the best\nmunicipal water supply In the country,\nand \\u25a0 when It does Marsdcn Manson's\nname will be among those mentioned\nmost frequently and with the most ap\npreciation, in the celebration.\nMAASOTV IS JUBILANT\nEngineer .Manson was jubilant when\na reporter for The Call met him up the\nroad yesterday afternoon -on the over\nland' limited.\n\"Do \\u25a0 you know what this means?\"\nexclaimed Manson. \"Do I you realize\nwhat we have acquired? Why, we\nhave:; within^ our reach ;\\u25a0 the 'greatest\nwater system in the whole iwJde' world!!\nIt means the purest arid .most health\nful 'drinking water 'obtaina.bl\u00ab>for our\n.children, for !f! f trie ;and for the\npeople-; generally: of the/ city. When\nyou realize that the. moWeminent phy\nsicians >teil' us that the health- of a\ncommunity is more closely, connected\nwith its water supply than any other\nsingle element you can \\u0084 understand\nwhat this will ao for San Francisco.\n\"We must not lose any time. We\nhave overcome the first and biggest\nobstacle, and now it is for the people\nof the -city to get together and carry\nthe project through. It will take time,\n.but there should \\u25a0, be no delay. The\npresident is with us; in fact, I found\nhim thoroughly familiar with every\nphase of the matter and eager to help\nSan Francisco in every way. Secretary\nGarfleld and Glffo'rd Pinchot, chief of\nthe forestry bureau, are also with; us\nin this' matter.\"\nThe agreement made by Engineer\nManson in the name' of the city with'\nthe government of the United States,\ncontaining nine stipulations as to the\nconditions under which the city may\navail itself of the reservoir sites, has\nDeen made public In dispatches from\nWashington. This will be\" submitted to\nthe board- of supervisors tomorrow and\nan Immediate ratification is anticipated.\nThis will close the bargain.\nWILL. PROPOSE ;BOZVD ISSUE\nEngineer Manson will then propose\nas the first step a bond issue of $2,000,\n000. With this he proposes to make\nthe' necessary, payments on the sites, to\npurchase the 142 miles of right of f way,\nto the' Sierra and, if- need be,\" to con\nstruct the first Lake Eleanor, dam.\n;\"Lake.Eleanor, when fully developed,\nwill give us a'daily supply of 60,000,\n000 gallons,\" said Manson, \"nearly\ndouble^the present .^needs of the city.\nLater w\u00ab can begin work on the Hetch\nHetchy reservoirs, and with these com\npleted, we shall have .a supply of be\ntween 200,000.000 and 300,000,000 gal\nlons daily, enough 1 to supply the cities\nabout the bay for a long time to come,\nwith a great deal left over.\"\n-The, total cost of the system, includ\ning a distributing plant, has been esti\nmated at\\ J39i000,600. Manson' figures'\nthat the? Sierra supply can be brought\nto/tho'city for J19.000.000.. This, ot\ncourse,'; does ''not include plpeage^\nthroughout the' municipality. Under\nthe. terms of the grant, the water may,\nbe utilized notiOnly for San Francisco\nbut for all the other bay cities as\nweii. 't'/',: ':\\u25a0, v \\u25a0 '--\\u25a0'\\u25a0'\n\\u25a0 Moreover, provision is made' that the\ncity may^avair itself, of the power/for\nlightlng'purposes. It' is only after it\nhas Uooked out for Its own needs and\n\"those -'of the adjacent m unlclpalitiea\n'that San Francisco must deliver to the\nirrigation \"districts. \\u25a0 The \u2022\u2022water and\nV power 'turned over to the irrigatlonists\nis to be sold at- cost.\n3IANY OBSTACLES OVERCOME\ni. \"We encountered any number: of ob\nstacles,\" said Manson, \"but I had good\nassistance. -Mr. .Charles W. Hornlck of\n.The; Call rendered valuable service In\nWashi ngton. He\" saw\" President Roose\nvelt and Secretary Garfleld \u2022\\u25a0* and was\nable to Khelp\"; the {project materially.'\nAf ter we had settled theYproblem pre\nContinued >on Page 20, Middle CoL 1\n\\u25a0\u2014 _ _ _ _ _ .j.\nJ.O. (Black) Hayes rubbing shoulders with Abe Ruef,\nwhose lessons in treachery he put to use for machine at Sacra\nmento convention. (From a photograph taken at Santa Cruz\nin 1906.) \\u25a0 :\\u25a0'\\u25a0;. V V\n\\u25a0 \\u25a0-.\\u25a0-.-\\u25a0-\\u25a0.\\u25a0 \\u25a0 \\u25a0 ..-._. \\u25a0 \\u25a0 \\u25a0\n\"Quit While Champ\" Is\nJohn L.'s Advice\nTells Roosevelt Nat to Stay in\nRing Until Some Phenome*\nnon Has Developed\nSPECIAL DISPATCH TO THE CALX,\nWASHINGTON, May 16.\u2014 When John\nL.- Sullivan called on President Roose\nvelt today to thank him ,for aiding his\nnephew, he improved the \\u25a0 opportunity\nto give the executive some advice on\nthe wisdom of ''quitting the game\"\nwhile he was still \"champ\", and not\nstay in the ring -too long\u2014 \"for,\" ob\nserved, Sullivan, \"a, guy is sure to get\nthe worst of it in the end.\"\nOn the fWhlte House\" steps after leav\ning the president,' Sullivan observed a\nparty of correspondents.\n\"You see, to die, a '.'champion you\nmust retire when youj are in /your,\nprime. --The old guy that* wrote the\nstory book about.. the pitcher. that went\nto the well once too- often was all\nright, all right; He had 'the t dope on\npast performances i and rio ..mistake, j\n\"Now Theodore Roosevelt' is 'a. cham\npion of champions. He- has won i the\nbelt In every class from feather weight\nup. He has met all comers and never\ntook the count. Why, there Taint \"a\nguy can train down arid- nieet.-hlm and\nstay the limit.- What ;doesf he do? Is\nhe going tor wait for some, phenom' to\ndevelop? Not'on your life.\". m\nSAY CANADIAN^PAPER\nMEN ARE LOSING MONEY;\ni Manufacturers Deny Combine\nand Declare Price Is at\nLowest\" Notch\nWASHINGTON, May 1 6.\u2014 Denial was\nmade today 'by. the paper\ncompany: and other .manufacturers :of\npaper* of theV charges maae, by. the\nAmerican newspaper \"publishers' asso\nciation that an agreement exists be\ntween them, either to\" raise the price\nof paper or to restrict the output. This\nevidence was given before- the special\ncommittee of the house \\u25a0 of representa\ntives that) isj investigating the wood\npuip-arid print paper question.\nThe claim also was made that Cana\ndian '\\u25a0\\u25a0'mills selling paper at\" 65 cents per\n100 pounds less, than American mills\nwere\" doing so at a loss, and that if nor\nmal conditions were* resumed in New\nEngland and Canada these prices would\nbe raised. iltalso;was a contention of\nthe witnesses today that the, present\nprice; of /paper is- the. lowest .they can\nirian\"ufactufo;it for, and: live.. \"\\u25a0 \"\\u25a0\nSAN FRANCISCAN WINS\nv HONORS'- IN v TECHNOLIOGY\nBradford Buttrick-Hofmes to Be\nBachelor of Science of Mas-\nsachusetts Institute\nSPECIAL DISPATCH ,TO THE CALL\nBOSTON, z May 16.\u2014 Among the suc\ncessful; candidates for* the bachelor of\nscience* degree^ at \u2022\\u25a0 the \"Mass'a'ch'usetta\nInstitute.- of Technology is;; Bradford\nButtrlck Holmes of San; Francisco, who\ncompletes .the -course\", of mining en\ngineering and /metallurgy. He will';'t^\ncelve\"a;degfeo \";-wltK\" honors^ ',\"at ;thercom\nmencem\u00a9nt:on; June, 8., v\nPAGES 25 TO 32 PRICE FIVE CENTS.\nThaw Is in Terror on\nWitness Stand\nAnswers to Jerome* s Questions\nIncoherent and Case Seems\nHopeless\nPOITGHKEEPSIB, IN. V., May 16.\u2014\nBefore Harry K. Thaw was- called, to\nthe witness stand tonight he begged\nnot to be forced to testify in his own\nbehalf In- the habeas \"corpus proceed\nings to get him out of Matteawan.\nJerome plied his questions as gently\nas possible -when he observed Thaw's\nterror and noted his incoherent an\nswers, some of which were almost un\nintelligible. Thaw shook like a leaf\nas Jerome began. His expression was\nas piteous as a child's. Jerome asked\nhim '.very^ gently '\\u25a0 if he understood the\nnature of the proceedings,' knew whata\nhabeas corpus was, and that Jif the\nproceedings were successful he would\nbe allowed to. go free. v\nThaw, bewildered, turned appeallngly\nto Justice Morschauser\" and ..asked If*\nas a result; of the habeas corpus, he\nmight be sent back to prison 1 to be\nre-tried on the murder charge.*\n...After, Jerome^ had talked .to him, as\na t child, i for some time, and elicited\nincoherent .replies, the prosecutor sud-.\ndenly announced: \"We rest, .your\nhonor.\" Thaw seemed greatly disap\npointed tonight at the turn .affairs had\ntaken. When led 'up stairs \\u25a0he was\nshaking like a leaf, -his. face had a\ndeep flush and his eyes stared wildly.\nPerspiration dripped* from his face and\nhands. From his appearance In court,\nand particularly from his pitiable\nshowing on the stand, any chance of\nhis escaping Matteawan on the ground\nof his! present sanity seem* hopeless.\n.The justice will-give his decision on\nMonday, ;Mayl2s.. t\nWHITE HOUSE \"RAIDED\"\nBY SERGEANTS AT ARMS\nCongressmen .Dragged From a\nGarden Party to Help\nMake Quorum\nSPECIAL DISPATCH TO THE CALL\nWASHINGTON,; May 16.\u2014 Sergeants'\nat arms of the house \\u25a0 yesterday nearly\nbroke up- the- garden party, of; Mrs.'\nRoosevelt at the White House in honor\nof the governors of states by techni\ncally putting under arrest 4 0 members\nof the house who were in attendance.\nBy! -their absence.s>h social enjoyment\nthe .members had- broken a quorum of\nthehouse and it was necessary to sum\nmon them before a legislative wheel\ncould be turned, -x\nAfter, searching -allj other. haunt 3of\nabsent members, the desperate resolve\nof \"raiding the White .House\" was un-\ndertaken.: How \\u25a0 the sergeants at arms\ngot. into theexecutive mansion is, yet\nunexplained.;''\nThe first thing the members, knew\nthey were being quietly that\nthere was a call of the house. The\n\"raid\" brought the members back '.to\nthe house decked out In all their social\nQnery, r ranging from-, frock coats to\ncutaways.\nTREACHERY OF\n\"BLACK\" HAVES\nFULLY PROVED\nSanta Clara County Politician's\nDenials Controverted by\nWitnesses\nDelivers League Delegation Into\nMachine's Hand by. His\nDouble Dealing\nEarns Contempt of Reform Ele\u00ab\nment, WhOe HernVs Men\nDeride Him\nThe record of proof against J. O.\nHayes in connection with his treach-\ncry to the Lincoln-Roosevelt repub\nlican league is now complete. In the\nattempted explanation of Hayes' con\nduct published yesterday in his paper,\nthe San Jose Mercury, are important\nstatements, that trustworthy wit\nnesses will emphatically controvert.\nHayes* denials that he delivered\nleague instructed delegates to the\nrailroad machine are met with over\nwhelming testimony, and he and Tom\nVlint Jr. of San Bentto present the sor\nriest political figures In California to\nday. ;r;r .v;\n\"Black\" Hayes* situation is a most\nunhappy one. Not only has he gained\nthe .contempt of the Lincoln-Roosevelt\nleague, but Cie railroad politicians\nlaugh about him and frankly say that\nthey would not trust him and that they\nhave no use for him.\n\"Hayes is the easiest thing in Cali\nfornia,\" said one machine boss at Sac\nramento, who was enjoying heartily\nthe trick that had been turned against\nthe league through the perfidy of the\nSan Josean.\nAs a matter of fact, the LJncoln-\nRoosevelt league men are well pleased\nover the thorough \"smoking out\" ot\nthe San Joaean, for they can easily win\nwithout him in the; Santa Clara valley.\nHe anfl his brother, Congressman\n\"Red\" Hayes, have been asserting all\nalong that thefc. wdald co-operato with\nthe league and were eager to help free\nthe state from Southern Pacific domi\nnation.\" Their good faith has always\nbeen doubted, but not until the de\nvelopments in Sacramento was there\nsufficient evidence to establish a posi\ntive classification of the \"ham and\negg x brothers,\", as the Abe Ruef push\nused to speak of them while they were\nall doing politics together In the fifth\ncongressional district.\nSUSPICION' IS AROUSED\nSuspicions among the leaguers were\nconfirmed by J. O. Hayes' offer, made In\nthe machine's state executive commit\ntee, of an outrageous party pledge for\nthe primary, whereby a republican in\norder to vote for delegates was to\npromise that at the election he would\nsupport even a yellow dog If It was put\non the ticket. The aim of the Herrin\nmen was to drive from the primary all\nself-respecting republicans who object\ned to taking: such an oath and who\nwere strong against machine- politics.\nWhea inquiry was made of the sin\ncere Lincoln-Roosevelt men of Santa\nClara- they explained that Hayes had\nundoubtedly been Imposed upon that\n.Walter Parker had undoubtedly taken\nadvantage of his dull wit and bad in\nduced him. to stand sponsor for the in\nfamous exaction by the state body. The\nleaguo leaders were asked to be chari\ntable.\nThey were told that, \"Red\" Hayes\nwould probably set \"Black\" Hayes right\nand that the brothers would assist ia\nthe cause of clean government in the\nstate', as they had actively done in their\nown county. In the local politics of\nSanta Clara county the Hayeses have\nunquestionably supported the better\nelement, but when their .own personal\nambitions became In volvfi in the larger\nstata and congressional affairs they\nhave cast their lot with Abe Ruef and\nhave been eager to gain th-e good will\nof Bess Herrin and his railroad ma-\nDRIVES HIM FROM COVER\nMatters were allowed to rest. by the\nLlncoln-Boosevelt men until the state\nconvention, when came that excellent\nopportunity to compel every man to\nstand up and \"be counted. Here J. O.\nHayes did his utmost to conceal his\npart, but he was driven from cover and\nforced to admit that he was an out and\nout railroad man.\nThe story of the political antics ot\nthe Hayes brothers Vls replete with\nlaughter and \"soft shoe\": episodes. Al\nthough they are men who belong on the\nclean, upright side of things, they have\nessayed to do tricky politics in fur\ntherance of their dream of \"Black\" as\ngovernor and \"Red\"\" as United States\nsenator.\nImmediately after the inauguration\nof the Lincoln-Roosevelt \\u25a0\\u25a0 movement,\nnine months ago some of its active\nfactors In Los Angeles were called up\nby long distance telephone from San\nJose, t asking them to meet Congress\nman Hayes, who would be down on the\nnext train. The congressman arrived\nas had been promised, and ho was\nbreathlessly eager to Join the league\nContinued ox Far a 34. Colnma J.","height":"26361","width":"19464"}}
